<dl id="n08049h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08049h">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08049h"> 49(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> I <font color="green">[&mdash;&mdash;]</font> / <font color="green">[&mdash;&mdash;]</font> / <font color="green">[&mdash;]</font> writer</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">La fig. 161 pr&eacute;sente d&apos;abord l&apos;&eacute;criture naturelle du scripteur, compliqu&eacute;e, sur&eacute;lev&eacute;e, orn&eacute;e, gonfl&eacute;e, jointoy&eacute;e, puis elle change tout-&agrave;-coup de caract&egrave;re et devient impersonelle &agrave; l&apos;occasion d&apos;un soulignement. Elle est du type calligraphique banal qu&apos;on appelle <i>officiel</i> parce qu&apos;il est impos&eacute; dans les administrations en vue d&apos;une plus grande lisibilit&eacute;. Ici les modifications de l&apos;&eacute;criture naturelle sont saisissantes, et l&apos;on voit justqu&apos;&agrave; quel point la contrainte calligraphique blanchit l&apos;&eacute;criture, mais elle ne lui enl&egrave;ve pas tout son caract&egrave;re. <br><font color="green">[Fig. 161 shows the writer&apos;s natural writing, complicated, elongated; ornate, blown-up, jointed; then it changes suddenly in character and becomes impersonal when it is underlined. This is of the commonplace calligraphic kind that we call official because it is imposed by administrations in order to ensure greater readability. Here the difference from natural writing is obvious, and we see at which point the calligraphic constraint discolours writing, although it does not take away all its character.]</font> <small> J Cr&eacute;pieux-Jamin, <a name="JCJL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JCJL"><cite title="source">Les &eacute;l&eacute;ments de l'&eacute;criture des canailles</cite></a> (1923) 283</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: This unit consists of three progressively indented wavy lines imitative of the various writing styles reproduced and referred to in the figures surrounding the text. A line, possibly stray, runs through the &lsquo;I&rsquo;, joining it with &lsquo;sentenced&rsquo; in the next unit. </mm> </dd></dl>
